# Accessing values 
df.loc[[rows], [columns]]  --> gives the entries of specific rows and columns mentioned here, accepts both numerical and text value, works with m:n value (include nth value)
df.iloc[[rows], [columns]] --> accepts only numerical values in m:n form (exclude nth value)
df.at['row name','column name'] --> gives the specific value at this intersection
df.iat['row name','column name'] --> gives the specific value at this intersection, accepts only integer value

#
df.sort_values(['xyz','abc'], ascending=[1,0])  --> sorts xyz in ascending and abc in descending
df.iterrows --> creates a loop passing values of index and row data in dataframe
df['xyz'].isin(['x','y','z'])  --> to provide values x, y and z only from the 'xyz' column
df.query(expression)   --> filters rows in a DataFrame using a SQL-like string expression


# regex  --> helps in sorting of data 
.        any character
\d       digit         
\D       not a digit
\w       word char      
\W       not a word char
\s       whitespace     
\S       not whitespace
^        start of string
$        end of string
*        0 or more
+        1 or more
?        0 or 1 (also makes quantifiers "lazy" when after * + ?)
{n,m}    between n and m repeats
[abc]    any one of a, b, c
[^abc]   anything except a, b, c
(...)    capturing group
(?:...)  non-capturing group
(?P<name>...)  named capturing group
|        OR / alternation
\        escape a special character

